1
00:00:07,835 --> 00:00:11,335
(peaceful, winding music)

2
00:02:02,126 --> 00:02:05,486
- Hello, my name is Albert Soady,

3
00:02:05,486 --> 00:02:07,819
and have I got a buck story for you.

4
00:02:08,726 --> 00:02:11,786
The tale I'm about to tell
starts in November of '89

5
00:02:11,786 --> 00:02:15,096
in the Soady deer camp, located just north

6
00:02:15,096 --> 00:02:18,266
of Escanaba, Michigan, otherwise known

7
00:02:18,266 --> 00:02:21,529
as the heart and soul
of the Upper Peninsula.

8
00:02:22,606 --> 00:02:24,996
That's north of the Mackinac Bridge

9
00:02:24,996 --> 00:02:27,743
and just south of heaven, for those of you

10
00:02:27,743 --> 00:02:28,893
who don't know nothing.

11
00:02:30,616 --> 00:02:33,966
For those that don't know
much about the Superior State,

12
00:02:33,966 --> 00:02:36,186
there's a couple things
that need to be explained.

13
00:02:36,186 --> 00:02:39,429
First thing is, in the U.P.,
we don't explain things.

14
00:02:40,296 --> 00:02:42,856
Second thing is, we got some of the best

15
00:02:42,856 --> 00:02:45,486
hunting and fishing in the whole world.

16
00:02:45,486 --> 00:02:48,776
Bear as tall as Norway pines.

17
00:02:48,776 --> 00:02:51,856
We got wolf, moose, beaver, wild turkey,

18
00:02:51,856 --> 00:02:56,856
quail, rabbit, fox, and,
of course, the bucks.

19
00:02:57,416 --> 00:03:02,009
Holy Wah, do we got bucks, big as Buicks!

20
00:03:02,926 --> 00:03:04,416
You can slice the venison off

21
00:03:04,416 --> 00:03:06,536
one Superior State buck and feed

22
00:03:06,536 --> 00:03:08,986
the whole state of Wisconsin.

23
00:03:08,986 --> 00:03:10,693
But there's another U.P.,

24
00:03:11,542 --> 00:03:13,566
the one that ain't in the travel books,

25
00:03:13,566 --> 00:03:16,259
the one that's older than
the very rocks it sits on,

26
00:03:17,416 --> 00:03:19,876
the one only the Indians understand.

27
00:03:19,876 --> 00:03:21,496
Don't get me started on them.

28
00:03:21,496 --> 00:03:23,546
My oldest boy married one.

29
00:03:23,546 --> 00:03:25,349
Strange gal, to say the least.

30
00:03:26,816 --> 00:03:28,586
I'm getting ahead of myself.

31
00:03:28,586 --> 00:03:31,339
As Great-Grandpa Alphonse
always used to say,

32
00:03:31,339 --> 00:03:33,386
when you don't know where to start,

33
00:03:33,386 --> 00:03:36,136
go back to the beginning.

34
00:03:36,136 --> 00:03:39,436
From the loins of our union,
Big Betty Belou and me

35
00:03:39,436 --> 00:03:42,349
bore two boys, Reuben and Remnar.

36
00:03:43,434 --> 00:03:44,446
Now, I'll tell ya right up front,

37
00:03:44,446 --> 00:03:46,729
they are not the sharpest
tools in the shed.

38
00:03:49,186 --> 00:03:50,956
Remnar turned out to be pretty much

39
00:03:50,956 --> 00:03:52,536
what you'd expect from somebody

40
00:03:52,536 --> 00:03:54,193
who went by the name of Remnar.

41
00:03:58,634 --> 00:04:02,551
But Reuben, well, Reuben
was a different story.

42
00:04:04,616 --> 00:04:07,126
Reuben spent his whole
life without hanging

43
00:04:07,126 --> 00:04:09,536
a single buck on the buck pole.

44
00:04:09,536 --> 00:04:11,426
That ain't a big to-do
if you're just another

45
00:04:11,426 --> 00:04:14,249
fudge-sucker bobbing over
the bridge, but for a Soady?

46
00:04:15,476 --> 00:04:18,359
Luckily that Injun gal had a way with him.

47
00:04:19,205 --> 00:04:20,616
- Wolf Moon Dance, will you still love me

48
00:04:20,616 --> 00:04:22,549
if I come back without a buck?

49
00:04:24,947 --> 00:04:25,780
- [Albert Voiceover] Now, some things fit

50
00:04:25,780 --> 00:04:27,003
together better than others,

51
00:04:27,003 --> 00:04:29,206
and it's hard to say how somebody

52
00:04:29,206 --> 00:04:32,736
who was so much a part of
the natural order of things

53
00:04:32,736 --> 00:04:37,479
would fall in love with
somebody who wasn't so natural.

54
00:04:43,056 --> 00:04:43,899
But she did.

55
00:04:48,837 --> 00:04:49,956
(gun clicks)

56
00:04:49,956 --> 00:04:54,536
And, lucky for him, 'cause
as Great-Grandpa Alphonse

57
00:04:54,536 --> 00:04:59,513
always said, behind every good
man is a woman who can hunt.

58
00:05:02,724 --> 00:05:05,032
(soft Native American music)

59
00:05:05,032 --> 00:05:07,032
- Forgot your lucky hat.

60
00:05:08,244 --> 00:05:10,206
- Can't go without this.

61
00:05:10,206 --> 00:05:11,596
- Boys, wave bye to Daddy, then I want

62
00:05:11,596 --> 00:05:13,086
you to run inside, okay?

63
00:05:13,086 --> 00:05:14,056
Go ahead.

64
00:05:14,056 --> 00:05:15,516
- Go get a deer, Dad.

65
00:05:15,516 --> 00:05:16,349
- Bye, boys.

66
00:05:22,216 --> 00:05:23,646
What?

67
00:05:23,646 --> 00:05:26,096
- Why does he never
invite me up to deer camp?

68
00:05:26,096 --> 00:05:26,946
- It's deer camp.

69
00:05:27,916 --> 00:05:29,336
- So?

70
00:05:29,336 --> 00:05:31,156
- So, it's deer camp.

71
00:05:31,156 --> 00:05:33,256
- Just thought maybe
if we hunted together.

72
00:05:33,256 --> 00:05:34,506
- If we hunted together, I'd be known

73
00:05:34,506 --> 00:05:37,006
as the buckless Yooper
whose wife shot him a buck.

74
00:05:38,026 --> 00:05:39,826
Look, I know what you're doing,

75
00:05:39,826 --> 00:05:41,136
and I love you for it, I really do,

76
00:05:41,136 --> 00:05:42,773
but I gotta do this on my own.

77
00:05:49,052 --> 00:05:51,872
(Reuben gasps)

78
00:05:51,872 --> 00:05:56,872
(Wolf Moon Dance speaking
foreign language)

79
00:06:08,756 --> 00:06:11,373
- Reuben, first, you must believe.

80
00:06:27,726 --> 00:06:29,396
- [Albert] Despite his little problem,

81
00:06:29,396 --> 00:06:32,786
Reuben hadn't missed an
opening day in over 30 years.

82
00:06:32,786 --> 00:06:34,616
- Best bait pile?

83
00:06:34,616 --> 00:06:36,989
Not corn, not carrots.

84
00:06:37,886 --> 00:06:39,896
Spoiled Brussels sprouts.

85
00:06:39,896 --> 00:06:41,676
See, deer aren't just colorblind.

86
00:06:41,676 --> 00:06:42,676
They're all-blind.

87
00:06:42,676 --> 00:06:43,546
And since they can't see,

88
00:06:43,546 --> 00:06:46,116
they gotta rely on the olfactory.

89
00:06:46,116 --> 00:06:48,339
Give 'em a little whiff
of the spoiled sprouts.

90
00:06:50,247 --> 00:06:52,543
Holy Wah, there he goes.

91
00:06:52,543 --> 00:06:55,626
(soft, twangy music)

92
00:06:59,533 --> 00:07:01,539
♪ Thought I knew a cold ♪

93
00:07:01,539 --> 00:07:04,669
♪ People I really thought I knew ♪

94
00:07:04,669 --> 00:07:06,915
♪ But there is such a freeze on me ♪

95
00:07:06,915 --> 00:07:09,373
♪ I'm fixing to turn blue ♪

96
00:07:09,373 --> 00:07:12,308
♪ Want you hand me down
my old winter coat ♪

97
00:07:12,308 --> 00:07:15,750
♪ No fire will warm me ♪

98
00:07:15,750 --> 00:07:19,394
(singing drowned out by squealing tires)

99
00:07:19,394 --> 00:07:21,749
♪ Freeze ♪

100
00:07:21,749 --> 00:07:24,832
(soft, twangy music)

101
00:07:36,082 --> 00:07:39,102
- Hey, look, it's Buckless Yooper!

102
00:07:39,102 --> 00:07:41,519
(kids shout)

103
00:07:45,747 --> 00:07:47,851
Hey, Buckless Yooper, Buckless Yooper!

104
00:07:47,851 --> 00:07:51,434
Hey, Buckless Yooper,
Buckless Yooper, hey!

105
00:07:52,569 --> 00:07:54,674
(tires screech)

106
00:07:54,674 --> 00:07:56,620
(kids laugh)

107
00:07:56,620 --> 00:07:59,703
(soft, twangy music)

108
00:08:01,959 --> 00:08:04,287
♪ Now it doesn't seem that long ago ♪

109
00:08:04,287 --> 00:08:07,370
♪ I was sitting on Daddy's knee ♪

110
00:08:07,370 --> 00:08:09,466
♪ Listening to the tales
that he would tell ♪

111
00:08:09,466 --> 00:08:12,582
♪ Some taller than the big pine trees ♪

112
00:08:12,582 --> 00:08:14,500
♪ He taught me about tradition ♪

113
00:08:14,500 --> 00:08:17,620
♪ Doing proud of the family name ♪

114
00:08:17,620 --> 00:08:22,620
♪ Hard as I might try mine
always seems the way of shame ♪

115
00:08:26,710 --> 00:08:29,085
♪ And I'm feeling so downhearted ♪

116
00:08:29,085 --> 00:08:31,995
♪ And I think I must just cry ♪

117
00:08:31,995 --> 00:08:34,671
♪ I'm afraid that if I do ♪

118
00:08:34,671 --> 00:08:39,671
♪ These tears are gonna freeze in my eye ♪

119
00:08:39,997 --> 00:08:42,188
♪ That might be okay ♪

120
00:08:42,188 --> 00:08:44,624
♪ 'Cause then I couldn't see ♪

121
00:08:44,624 --> 00:08:47,006
♪ All the things that keep going wrong ♪

122
00:08:47,006 --> 00:08:49,471
♪ The way they all look at me ♪

123
00:08:49,471 --> 00:08:51,959
♪ Back there wishing I would go ♪

124
00:08:51,959 --> 00:08:55,666
♪ Over that big old bridge and leave ♪

125
00:08:55,666 --> 00:08:58,022
♪ Lord have mercy, get me through ♪

126
00:08:58,022 --> 00:09:01,355
♪ This hard luck freeze ♪

127
00:09:03,088 --> 00:09:06,171
(soft, twangy music)

128
00:09:14,142 --> 00:09:14,975
- Hello!

129
00:09:16,250 --> 00:09:17,083
- Hello!

130
00:09:18,295 --> 00:09:19,128
- Is this the Soady deer camp?

131
00:09:19,128 --> 00:09:20,126
- You found her.

132
00:09:20,126 --> 00:09:21,866
- The world famous Soady deer camp?

133
00:09:21,866 --> 00:09:22,736
- One and the same.

134
00:09:22,736 --> 00:09:24,966
- Yeah, is that Albert
Soady's sweet sap whisky

135
00:09:24,966 --> 00:09:26,122
over there I see?

136
00:09:26,122 --> 00:09:26,955
- Might be so lucky.

137
00:09:26,955 --> 00:09:29,600
- Well, better have me a snort, eh?

138
00:09:29,600 --> 00:09:30,433
- You know it's good for ya.

139
00:09:30,433 --> 00:09:31,689
- How ya feeling, Pop?

140
00:09:32,745 --> 00:09:35,454
- If I felt any better, I'd be dangerous.

141
00:09:35,454 --> 00:09:38,292
(Reuben chuckles)

142
00:09:38,292 --> 00:09:39,125
- Oh, wow.

143
00:09:52,819 --> 00:09:54,119
A little heavy on the sap.

144
00:09:54,994 --> 00:09:55,827
- A little what?

145
00:09:55,827 --> 00:09:57,616
- On the sap, it's a
little heavy on the sap.

146
00:09:57,616 --> 00:09:59,446
- The sap's what's makes it.

147
00:09:59,446 --> 00:10:01,076
- Yeah, well, that may be,
but, if I didn't know better,

148
00:10:01,076 --> 00:10:03,479
I'd say I just drunk from
a bottle of maple syrup.

149
00:10:04,356 --> 00:10:05,616
- [Albert] Give me the damn jar back.

150
00:10:05,616 --> 00:10:06,449
- All right-

151
00:10:06,449 --> 00:10:07,816
- A man who can't look another man

152
00:10:07,816 --> 00:10:09,376
right in the hairy eyeball and tell him

153
00:10:09,376 --> 00:10:11,746
he's heavy on the sap ain't much of a man.

154
00:10:11,746 --> 00:10:13,636
Maybe it'd be better if I
took the sap out altogether.

155
00:10:13,636 --> 00:10:15,026
Would that make you happy?

156
00:10:15,026 --> 00:10:16,246
- Well, I wouldn't think of Aunt Jemima

157
00:10:16,246 --> 00:10:18,166
every time I took a snort,
I can tell you that.

158
00:10:18,166 --> 00:10:20,294
- Well, I ain't about to
do it, so put that down.

159
00:10:20,294 --> 00:10:22,296
That year, camp was as
tense as a moose's butt

160
00:10:22,296 --> 00:10:23,596
during fly season.

161
00:10:23,596 --> 00:10:24,846
Remnar didn't help.

162
00:10:24,846 --> 00:10:25,679
- Hello!

163
00:10:28,126 --> 00:10:29,872
Is this the Soady deer camp?

164
00:10:29,872 --> 00:10:30,705
- You found her!

165
00:10:30,705 --> 00:10:31,916
- The world famous Soady deer camp?

166
00:10:31,916 --> 00:10:33,413
- The one and the same.
- The one and the same.

167
00:10:33,413 --> 00:10:34,246
- And is that a pint of Albert Soady's

168
00:10:34,246 --> 00:10:35,433
sweet sap whisky I see?

169
00:10:35,433 --> 00:10:36,816
- You like pancakes?

170
00:10:36,816 --> 00:10:37,876
- A little heavy on the sap, eh?

171
00:10:37,876 --> 00:10:39,161
- Oh yeah, no kidding.

172
00:10:39,161 --> 00:10:39,994
- But that's what makes it-

173
00:10:39,994 --> 00:10:40,827
- You're late.

174
00:10:40,827 --> 00:10:41,660
You're supposed to be here at six, eh?

175
00:10:41,660 --> 00:10:42,493
- Black leather, fudge-sucking-

176
00:10:42,493 --> 00:10:43,486
- I stopped off to the porcelain bus,

177
00:10:43,486 --> 00:10:44,319
picked up the beer,

178
00:10:44,319 --> 00:10:45,152
thank you very much.
- I'm not talking about that

179
00:10:45,152 --> 00:10:45,985
and you know that.

180
00:10:45,985 --> 00:10:47,684
You're supposed to steer
clear of her, Remnar.

181
00:10:47,684 --> 00:10:48,766
- Did you want the beer or not?

182
00:10:48,766 --> 00:10:49,846
- I don't care about the beer.
- I don't drink nothing

183
00:10:49,846 --> 00:10:51,416
that's already been drunk before.

184
00:10:51,416 --> 00:10:53,776
- Pop, I got it, okay, I got it.

185
00:10:53,776 --> 00:10:56,180
- They was playing this game, eh?

186
00:10:56,180 --> 00:10:58,076
(people chattering)

187
00:10:58,076 --> 00:10:59,626
They put all the guys on one side,

188
00:10:59,626 --> 00:11:01,176
and all the girls on the other.

189
00:11:02,286 --> 00:11:04,995
And we each got a cue stick
off of the pool table there.

190
00:11:04,995 --> 00:11:06,376
(people chattering)

191
00:11:06,376 --> 00:11:10,006
And the gals all got a
roll of toilet paper.

192
00:11:10,006 --> 00:11:15,006
(bluesy bar music)
(people shouting)

193
00:12:12,816 --> 00:12:14,316
First couple to jam their cue stick

194
00:12:14,316 --> 00:12:18,126
into the toilet roll gets
a free case of Leinenkugel,

195
00:12:18,126 --> 00:12:20,116
thank you very much.

196
00:12:20,116 --> 00:12:21,436
- [Reuben] She's married, Remnar.

197
00:12:21,436 --> 00:12:22,746
- I couldn't help myself, eh?

198
00:12:22,746 --> 00:12:24,496
The girl's got a tongue of a trout.

199
00:12:26,916 --> 00:12:28,916
- Your mother had the tongue of a trout.

200
00:12:51,056 --> 00:12:53,056
- She was licking me like a dog's balls.

201
00:12:53,056 --> 00:12:54,786
- Her husband filed a restraining order.

202
00:12:54,786 --> 00:12:56,366
- Yeah, I know, I know, but she's got

203
00:12:56,366 --> 00:12:58,146
a hot nose, hands like a logger.

204
00:12:58,146 --> 00:12:59,936
This girl can split wood.

205
00:12:59,936 --> 00:13:01,826
- [Albert] Your mother could split wood.

206
00:13:03,366 --> 00:13:04,256
- Did you bring the pasties?

207
00:13:04,256 --> 00:13:05,326
Tell me you brought the pasties.

208
00:13:05,326 --> 00:13:06,159
- We're gonna eat like kings.

209
00:13:06,159 --> 00:13:07,376
- You know me, you know how I am.

210
00:13:07,376 --> 00:13:08,596
I am a creature with habits.

211
00:13:08,596 --> 00:13:09,986
If things aren't just so,

212
00:13:09,986 --> 00:13:11,280
things won't work out.
- Things won't work out.

213
00:13:11,280 --> 00:13:12,122
- That's right.

214
00:13:12,122 --> 00:13:12,955
Tell me again you brought the pasties.

215
00:13:12,955 --> 00:13:13,788
- I took care of it, eh?

216
00:13:13,788 --> 00:13:15,041
- Beautiful!

217
00:13:15,041 --> 00:13:16,206
Is this heaven or is this heaven, eh?

218
00:13:16,206 --> 00:13:17,039
- This is heaven.

219
00:13:17,039 --> 00:13:19,456
- I think I look forward to
opening day of deer season

220
00:13:19,456 --> 00:13:21,379
more than any other day of the year.

221
00:13:23,086 --> 00:13:25,396
It's like Christmas, with guns.

222
00:13:25,396 --> 00:13:26,656
You feeling lucky this year, Pop?

223
00:13:26,656 --> 00:13:29,006
'Cause I'm feeling lucky.

224
00:13:29,006 --> 00:13:31,896
- Give a man a little luck and
anything will do for brains.

225
00:13:31,896 --> 00:13:33,836
- Yeah, toss a little over this way.

226
00:13:33,836 --> 00:13:35,666
- I was driving up to camp tonight,

227
00:13:35,666 --> 00:13:37,716
I swear to God I had one of those things.

228
00:13:38,806 --> 00:13:40,886
What do you call those things
you get when you're driving?

229
00:13:40,886 --> 00:13:42,466
- Blackouts?
- Blackouts?

230
00:13:42,466 --> 00:13:43,666
- One of those things that flash

231
00:13:43,666 --> 00:13:46,696
across your mind like a dream,
only you're not dreaming.

232
00:13:46,696 --> 00:13:47,529
- A vision?

233
00:13:47,529 --> 00:13:49,704
- I was driving up to camp, eh?

234
00:13:49,704 --> 00:13:50,966
Thinking about what scope to use,

235
00:13:50,966 --> 00:13:53,465
which socks to wear, how
much beer to take, you know?

236
00:13:53,465 --> 00:13:54,298
- The essentials.

237
00:13:54,298 --> 00:13:56,316
- Right, when all of a sudden,
right there in front of me

238
00:13:56,316 --> 00:13:58,795
is a 50-point buck.

239
00:13:58,795 --> 00:14:00,136
- A 50-point buck?

240
00:14:00,136 --> 00:14:01,246
- That's what I said.

241
00:14:01,246 --> 00:14:03,856
- There is no such thing
as a 50-point buck.

242
00:14:03,856 --> 00:14:05,546
- I know, I know, I know,
I said the same thing.

243
00:14:05,546 --> 00:14:06,646
I said, this can't be so.

244
00:14:06,646 --> 00:14:08,616
I mean, you know, a 50-point buck,

245
00:14:08,616 --> 00:14:12,466
but I looked again, and
there he was, as real as you.

246
00:14:12,466 --> 00:14:14,706
And the thing was, he didn't go away.

247
00:14:14,706 --> 00:14:17,748
I just kept seeing him and
seeing him and seeing him.

248
00:14:17,748 --> 00:14:19,116
- And you're still
driving this whole time?

249
00:14:19,116 --> 00:14:21,246
- I do not believe I was, no.

250
00:14:21,246 --> 00:14:22,626
Somebody had their hands on the wheel,

251
00:14:22,626 --> 00:14:24,696
but I could not tell you
for sure they was mine.

252
00:14:24,696 --> 00:14:27,576
- Holy Wah.
- Holy Wah is right.

253
00:14:27,576 --> 00:14:29,186
So I jump out of the truck,

254
00:14:29,186 --> 00:14:31,466
and still he don't move a muscle.

255
00:14:31,466 --> 00:14:33,656
It was like he was waiting for me,

256
00:14:33,656 --> 00:14:36,566
just standing there, tall and proud,

257
